  "text": "Clearly T is transitive if and only if there exists an ordering σ on V such that for every u ∈ V and v ∈ V with σ(u) < σ(v) (also denoted u < σ v) then uv ∈ A. Such an ordering is called transitive. We use T σ = (V, A, σ) to denote a tournament whose vertices are ordered with respect to some ordering σ. An arc vu ∈ A such that u < σ v is called backward in T σ . In other words, T is transitive if and only if there exists a total ordering σ of its vertices such that T σ does not contains any backward arc. Hereafter, a directed triangle will be called a conflict. Our kernel uses the following rule from [CITATION_1] .",
